ðŸ”¬ Experiment 4: Pulling and Running Docker Images (note the r32.6.1 corresponding to your jetpack 4.6) 
Step 1: Pull a Docker image
sudo docker pull nvcr.io/nvidia/l4t-pytorch:r32.6.1-pth1.8-py3
________________________________________
Step 2: Run a Docker container
sudo docker run -it --rm \
  --network host \
  --volume /home/nvidia/pose:/home/pose \
  --device /dev/video0 \
  --runtime nvidia \
  <image_id or repo:tag>

You can get image_id when you do docker images.

Step 3: Use exit command to quit a docker.

Inside a docker you can create data, edit code, install softwares like it was a normal machine
You will loose it on exit.
If you want to retain it, dont use the --rm option while running the docker. After you make changes in the docker, exit. 

Step 4: You can check the container (instance of docker image) you ran using
sudo docker ps -a

Step 5: You can commit the changes using the container_id (you can see it with the docker ps -a command) , and a new name
sudo docker commit container_id mydoc:v1
